Phase-Specific Guidelines
I. Abstract Phase (Precision Required)
• Goal: Create a concise yet comprehensive summary of the entire study that accurately reflects the research gap, methodology, key findings, and implications.
• Researcher Responsibilities:
Gap Identification: Precisely locate the central contradiction in the research field and identify unresolved key issues in existing theories or practices.
• Communication: "I am in the Abstract phase. I have identified the following research gap: [specific gap]. Does this align with our understanding of the field's current limitations?"
Methodology Conciseness: Briefly describe the core technical approach or analytical framework used to address the identified gap.
Data Specification: Clearly state the key characteristics of the data used to validate the methodology (e.g., sample size, temporal/spatial dimensions, variable properties).
Finding Distillation: Condense the breakthrough conclusions derived from data analysis into precise statements.
Significance Clarification: Articulate the contribution of these findings to the theoretical framework of the discipline or their innovative significance for practical applications.
Peer Review: Seek feedback on whether the abstract accurately represents the research and effectively communicates its value.
• Communication: "I have drafted the abstract. It emphasizes [key elements]. Does this capture the essence of our research appropriately?"
II. Introduction Phase
• Goal: Establish the research context, clearly define the problem, and outline the paper structure, creating a logical foundation for the study.
• Researcher Responsibilities:
Background Development: From the discipline's developmental context or practical needs, demonstrate the contemporary necessity of the research problem.
• Communication: "In developing the introduction, I'm framing the background around [key context]. Should we emphasize different contextual elements?"
Problem Delimitation: Based on background analysis, focus on specific research pain points and clarify the boundaries and core elements of the problem.
Research Evolution: Trace the development of key research achievements in the field chronologically or logically, constructing an academic development map.
Limitation Identification: Systematically analyze deficiencies in previous research regarding methodological design, data coverage, or theoretical interpretation.
Research Positioning: Clearly explain the solution, technical path, and expected outcomes proposed to address these limitations, defining the research scope (what is included/excluded).
Structure Outline: Provide an overview of how subsequent sections progressively advance the argument, forming a logical 闭环 (closed loop).
Validation: Confirm that the introduction effectively establishes the research rationale and leads naturally to the methodology.
III. Literature Review Phase
• Goal: Position the research within existing scholarship, demonstrating command of relevant literature and clearly establishing the research gap.
• Researcher Responsibilities:
Gap Depth Analysis: Through comparative analysis of authoritative studies, quantitatively or qualitatively demonstrate the extent of existing research gaps.
• Communication: "In the literature review, I've identified [specific gaps] through analysis of [key studies]. Should we include additional literature to strengthen this analysis?"
Theoretical-Methodological Genealogy: Construct a 谱系 (genealogy) of theoretical frameworks related to the research question, evaluating the applicability boundaries of each approach.
Cross-Disciplinary Integration (if applicable): Justify the introduction of methodologies from other disciplines, analyzing their adaptability and innovative potential in the current field.
Synthesis: Integrate literature findings to create a coherent narrative that justifies the current research approach.
IV. Methodology Phase
• Goal: Provide a detailed, reproducible description of how the research was conducted, enabling other researchers to replicate the study.
• Researcher Responsibilities:
Design Logic: Explain the rationale for selecting the research paradigm (e.g., empirical research, simulation research) and present the technical roadmap.
• Communication: "I've outlined our methodological approach as [description]. Does this adequately address potential validity concerns?"
Data Acquisition Strategy: Explain criteria for selecting data types (independent variables, dependent variables, control variables), collection tools, and quality control methods.
Analysis Process Construction: Detail data processing steps. If models are involved, explain:
Model assumptions and parameter settings
Validation methods and evaluation indicators
Comparative dimensions with traditional methods
Reproducibility Check: Ensure sufficient detail for other researchers to replicate the methodology.
V. Data Phase
• Goal: Describe the dataset comprehensively, establishing its suitability for addressing the research question.
• Researcher Responsibilities:
Dataset Characteristics: Describe the authority of data sources, the appropriateness of collection periods, and provide statistical distribution characteristics of key variables (mean, standard deviation, quantiles, etc.).
• Communication: "I've described our dataset as [summary]. Should we emphasize different characteristics or provide additional descriptive statistics?"
Preprocessing Procedures: Explain specific operations and scientific rationale for data cleaning (outlier handling), transformation (standardization, normalization), and integration.
Limitation Disclosure: Identify any limitations in the dataset that might affect results or generalizability.
VI. Results Phase
• Goal: Present research findings objectively and neutrally, without interpretation or speculation.
• Researcher Responsibilities:
Core Finding Presentation: Objectively display statistically validated key results in order of priority related to the research questions.
• Communication: "I've organized the results around [key findings]. Does this structure effectively highlight the most significant outcomes?"
Trend Analysis: Present patterns or dynamic change characteristics implied in the data through visualizations.
Anomaly Identification: Flag noteworthy special data points, describing only the phenomena without attribution.
Validation Results: Report data verifying the methodology's effectiveness (e.g., accuracy rates, significance levels).
Objectivity Check: Ensure results are presented without interpretive language or speculative claims.
VII. Discussion Phase
• Goal: Interpret findings, relate them to existing literature, and explain their significance.
• Researcher Responsibilities:
Horizontal Comparison: Quantitatively compare the study's results with similar research, analyzing consistencies and differences.
• Communication: "In the discussion, I'm comparing our findings with [key studies], noting [similarities/differences]. Should we emphasize different comparative dimensions?"
Internal Connection: Reveal logical relationships between various results, constructing a conclusion system.
Difference Attribution: For discrepancies with previous research, analyze potential causes from three aspects:
Sample heterogeneity (e.g., population characteristics, temporal/spatial differences)
Methodological differences (e.g., indicator selection, model settings)
Potential mechanisms (influential pathways not previously noted)
Significance Elaboration: Explain the broader implications of the findings for the field.
VIII. Conclusion Phase
• Goal: Provide a concise synthesis of the research, highlighting its contributions, limitations, and implications for future work.
• Researcher Responsibilities:
Core Conclusion Distillation: Use academic language to highly summarize the research's breakthrough achievements, avoiding repetition of results descriptions.
• Communication: "I've drafted conclusions emphasizing [key points]. Do these effectively capture the significance of our research?"
Theoretical-Practical Contributions: Clearly identify the research's contributions to disciplinary theory or specific guidance value for industry decision-making.
Research Limitations: Objectively explain two categories of limitations:
Scope limitations (e.g., samples covering only specific populations)
Methodological limitations (e.g., insufficient data timeliness, simplified model assumptions)
Future Directions: Based on limitations, propose actionable research recommendations, such as:
Expanding research scope (e.g., cross-cultural validation)
Improving methodological systems (e.g., integrating multi-source data)
Deepening mechanism research (e.g., mediating effect analysis)
Final Validation: Ensure conclusions directly address the research questions posed in the introduction and reflect the significance of the findings.
