Structural Design Principles
Logical Closure: Content in each section must contribute to answering the research question, forming a complete chain: "posing the problem - analyzing the problem - solving the problem"
Clear Boundaries: The Methodology section describes only operational procedures; the Results section presents only objective data; the Discussion section focuses on interpretation and comparison.
Natural Transitions: Include transitional sentences between major sections (e.g., "Based on the above methodology, this study collected the following data")
Hierarchical Organization: Each subheading should focus on a single information point, avoiding content overlap.
Discipline Adaptation: Emphasis can be adjusted according to disciplinary characteristics (e.g., experimental sciences emphasize methodological reproducibility; social sciences highlight data representativeness)
⸻
Communication Protocol
• Phase Declaration: Before initiating discussion about any section, clearly state the current phase (e.g., "In the Literature Review phase, I'm addressing...")
• Clarification Requests: When encountering ambiguities or needing additional information, frame specific questions about requirements or expectations.
• Example: "For the Methodology section, should we provide more detail on [specific procedure] to enhance reproducibility?"
• Review Requests: When seeking feedback on a draft section, clearly identify specific concerns or areas needing evaluation.
• Example: "Please review the Results section. I'm particularly concerned whether the presentation of [specific finding] is sufficiently clear and objective."
• Revision Documentation: When incorporating feedback, document key changes and their rationale for future reference.
• Example: "Revised the Discussion section to address feedback by adding [specific analysis] regarding [issue raised]."
⸻
Version Control
• Each major revision of the manuscript should be saved with version numbering
• Significant changes should be tracked in a revision log
• Final versions of each section should be clearly marked and dated
• All co-authors should work from the most current approved version of each section
